Related Content
            





                            11-year-old entrepreneur lands Starbucks deal                        





                            Austin organic pet products maker swims in the 'Shark Tank'                        





                            Mentoring Monday: 'Invigorating' group of female professionals connect                        



 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Privacy and Views Abound                




See All Homes of the Day





 











 Enlarge





                Mikaila Ulmer has visited Washington, D.C. multiple times, including in March for the… more 

                Jacob Christian Ulmer            








 



What started as a passion project for Mikaila Ulmer has turned into something much bigger.
The 11-year-old Austin entrepreneur and her family recently changed the name of their company from Bee Sweet Lemonade to Me & the Bees LLC, reflecting a desire to move into other products.













 Enlarge






                            Mikaila Ulmer has visited Washington, D.C. multiple times, including in March for the… more 
Jacob Christian Ulmer










 


“When I started, I thought it was going to be a one-time thing but it actually grew and I realized the name wasn’t right,” Mikaila said.




An appearance on ABC-TV’s “Shark Tank” in March 2015 was the start of a whirlwind publicity tour. She has visited the White House multiple times — to attend a 2015 state dinner, then again in March of this year as a guest chef at the White House Easter Egg Roll. What’s more, she spoke in May at a New York City event hosted by Microsoft Corp. highlighting standout students and appeared on “Good Morning America” to promote her business —and win over the hearts of millions of viewers. Between all of those engagements, plus the regular childhood obligations of school and playtime with friends, she found time to speak to Austin Business Journal about her plans.
Me & the Bees has more than doubled production in the past year — the company sold 89,666 bottles of lemonade from January-May 2016, up from 33,879 bottles in the same period in 2015. The company has also reached a distribution agreement with Rhode Island-based United Natural Foods Inc. — one of the nation’s largest distributors of natural and organic foods with 2015 revenue of $8.2 billion — which got Me & the Bees lemonade onto the shelves of 39 Austin-area Starbucks store for an eight-week trial.
The company’s lemonade is also sold in more than 70 stores throughout the Southeast U.S., including 55 Whole Foods Market Inc. locations.




 


“It has been super cool traveling to all of these different places and meeting really cool people,” Mikaila said.
Plans aren’t solidified but she is considering new product lines in gift merchandise plus food and drinks. She also wants to continue motivational speaking and will travel to Cape Town, South Africa this summer for a summit hosted by the Dell Women’s Entrepreneur Network.

Most of Me & the Bee’s expansion has been funded by revenue growth. The company also received an early $35,000 loan from the city of Austin and is now considering seeking investments. D’Andra Ulmer, Mikaila’s mother, said the company is open to venture capital and other forms of funding “so we can finance explosive growth.”
No matter what direction the business takes, D’Andra said she was “so proud” of her daughter’s achievements — both as an entrepreneur and as a young girl making a big imprint on the world.
“As a parent, what’s really important is that she’s a good person, she’s kind, she’s respectful, a good friend and a good big sister,” D’Andra said.
Mikaila started her business in part to raise money for bee preservation groups. Its wild success has taught her one very important lesson.
“You don’t have to be an adult to solve problems,” Mikaila said.

Will Anderson coordinates digital coverage of business news and coverages a wide variety of topics, from consumer goods to health care.












